Sync vs Async vs defer

JavaScript Loading Types in HTML
When you include JavaScript in an HTML file using <script>, the browser can load and execute it in three different ways:

1ï¸âƒ£ Synchronous (sync by default)
2ï¸âƒ£ Asynchronous (async)
3ï¸âƒ£ Deferred (defer)

1ï¸âƒ£ Synchronous (Default Behavior)
ğŸ”¹ If you add a script like this:
<script src="script.js"></script>

ğŸ‘‰ The browser stops everything, downloads the JavaScript file, and executes it before continuing to load the rest of the page.

ğŸ“Œ Effect:
Blocks HTML parsing â†’ Slows down page loading.
Good for scripts that must run before the page is shown.
2ï¸âƒ£ Async (async)

ğŸ”¹ If you add a script like this:
<script src="script.js" async></script>
ğŸ‘‰ The browser downloads the script while parsing HTML but executes it immediately when itâ€™s ready.

ğŸ“Œ Effect:

Faster page load than sync scripts.
Execution order is unpredictable (whichever script loads first runs first).
Best for independent scripts (like analytics).

3ï¸âƒ£ Defer (defer)
<script src="script.js" defer></script>
ğŸ‘‰ The browser downloads the script while parsing HTML but waits until the entire HTML is loaded before running it.

ğŸ“Œ Effect:

Doesnâ€™t block HTML parsing.
Scripts run in order (unlike async).
Best for scripts that modify the page after it loads.
When to Use What?
âœ… Use synchronous scripts if the JavaScript must run before the page is shown (not recommended for large scripts).
âœ… Use async for scripts that donâ€™t depend on HTML, like ads or analytics.
âœ… Use defer for scripts that need the full HTML before running (recommended for most cases).
